<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-12-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-12-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="728" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d728">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Takahira</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-11"><hi rend="italic">December 11,
                                    1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 88.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of the telegram, dated the 4th instant, from Baron Komura to
                            you, in which he announces the death of Mr. Alfred E. Buck, United
                            States minister to Japan, and expresses the condolence of the Japanese
                            Government at the sad event.</p>
                        <p>In reply I beg to say that the Government of the United States greatly
                            appreciates the courtesy and sympathy of the Japanese Government.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>